abstract: ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla., March 31. -- St. Augustine is never so charming as in the early Spring days when the visitors who have been further south gather here to finish a well-spent Winter. Although many of the Winter guests are turning their faces toward home the hotels are well filled. Every hour yachts and motor boats carry visitors to the beaches, to Crescent Beach, ten miles away, or further, to Matansas.

abstract: LENS, March 31. -- The survivors of the Courrieres mine disaster of March 10, who were brought to the surface from Pit 2 yesterday, passed a good night. abstract: WILKESBARRE, Penn., April 1. -- Mine workers' unions throughout the anthracite region met this afternoon and tonight, and without exception agreed to obey the suspension order, effective tomorrow morning. The union leaders declare that not a man except the engineers, firemen, and pump runners will report for work, and that these men will be limited to the number required to keep the mines free from water, in compliance with the order issued by President Mitchell.

abstract: TUSKEGEE, Ala., April 1. -- The celebration of the twenty-fifth anniversary of the foundation of the Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute was begun here to-day. abstract: The axle of a rear truck of Car 101 of a local train on the Brooklyn Bridge snapped like a pipestem yesterday morning and tied up traffic on the bridge for three hours. The Train was on its way from Brooklyn to Manhattan and was about 300 feet from the Brooklyn anchorage. It was 7:40 A.M., and all of the bridge trains were crowded. Car 101 was the motor car of a five-car train.

abstract: CLEVELAND, Ohio, April 2. -- The Ohio coal operators are planning a finish fight not only with the miners, but with the Pittsburg Coal Company, whose President, Francis L. abstract: ALBANY, N.Y., April 3. -- After a fight of four hours the Assembly to-day recommitted the Raines-Murphy Recount bill by a vote of 83 to 47. It is conceded that the measure is dead. abstract: COLUMBUS, Ohio, April 3. -- The champion New Yorks received a pleasant greeting here to-day, the weather being the most delightful of their training tour. They got great practice this afternoon by defeating the Columbus team 5 to 0. There was not much hitting in the game. Robertaille, late of Pittsburg, held the New Yorkers down to one drive in the first three innings.

abstract: The People's Institute held a large meeting in Cooper Union last night to consider the question of the city's water supply. The meeting was virtually a protest against the plan to bring water from the Catskills. abstract: CAMBRIDGE, Mass., April 3. -- The Harvard Athletic Committee declared to-day in favor of playing intercollegiate football during the season of 1906. abstract: LONDON, April 3. -- In the House of Lords to-day Lord Northbourne asked the Government if it would lay on the table any Consular or other reports concerning the anti-Jewish outpages in Russia. abstract: The extent to which the improved condition of Mexico's monetary system is benefiting foreign capital invested in that country is indicated by the annual report of the National Railroad of Mexico, issued yesterday. abstract: PRINCETON, N.J., April 9. -- Princeton's tennis team is preparing for an active season and has arranged four of its dates in addition to the intercollegiate matches. Penn is to be played twice, once in Philadelphia and once at Princeton, while a match will likely be arranged with Harvard. The dates are: May 12, Penn at Philadelphia; 20, Columbia at Princeton; June 2, Yale at Princeton; 9, Penn at Princeton.

abstract: NAPLES, April 9. -- Reports of fatalities consequent upon the eruption of Mount Vesuvius are coming in. According to information received late to-night, probably 500 lives were lost. abstract: In a nervy finish Ora Morningstar, the American, last night defeated Louis Cure, the French billiardist, by the score of 500 points to 463. The contest was the opening of the international championship tournament in the concert hall of Madison Square Garden. The ending was sensational. When Cure had turned into his final hundred his score showed 410, while Morningstar's string was 287, a total of 123 behind the Frenchman.

abstract: WASHINGTON, April 9. -- In a driving rain and on a track that was nearly fetlock deep in soft mud, to-day's races at Benning were started. The rain, which began last night, ceased after a while, but the conditions were about as unfavorable for good sport as they well could be. The result was not only a greatly reduced attendance, but also reduced fields. Four favorites and two strong second choices won the six races.

abstract: VINELAND, N.J., April 12. -- Warren P. Edgarton, soldier, school teacher, lecturer, ex-Assistant Superintendent of the United States Mail Service and Special Agent for twenty-seven years, died last night. Buck installed an X-ray apparatus in the Edgarton household and treated the patient both with X-rays and radium.

abstract: Antonio Drilleo, 34 years old, was shot and stabbed to death in the hallway of the tenement house at 128 Cherry Street just after 1 o'clock this morning. The police have in custody his brother, Alphonse, 24 years old, charged with being the murderer. The prisoner is said to have been arrested with a smoking revolver in hand, while two blood-stained stilettos were found in the hallway by the side of the dead Drilleo.

abstract: The unusually elaborate Easter preparations which had been made in the churches of New York were wasted to a certain extent on account of the inclement weather. abstract: JEFFERSON CITY, Mo., April 16. -- Gov. abstract: LONDON, April 17. -- New York's persistence in withdrawing gold from this market is beginning to disturb London financiers. abstract: The effects upon the stock market of the calamity which last week overtook San Francisco were felt chiefly on Thursday, the day after the news reached this city. abstract: WILKESBARRE, April 27. -- The anthracite operators' refusal of the miners' last propositions has cast a pall of gloom over the entire anthracite region. abstract: In one of the fastest and snappiest games of the season, Brooklyn defeated Philadelphia yesterday at Washington Park by the score of 1 to 0. It was another contribution day, and more than 10,000 persons witnessed the contest. There was an entire absence of any disorder, and for the first time this season Brooklyn showed real playing strength. Both teams played without an error, and the two pitchers contested evenly throughout after the first inning.

abstract: As is inevitable in all new countries, the number of crimes is very high in the United States of America, but the New York papers assert that the crimes committed last year are far in excess of those perpetrated in preceding years. abstract: Mrs. Anna Ortowitz of 346 East Houston Street attempted suicide yesterday afternoon by throwing herself on the track in front of a north-bound elevated train at Second Avenue and Twenty-third Street. abstract: ATHENS, April 29. -- The Olympic programme to-day included a remarkable aquatic display and a performance of Sophocles's tragedy, "Oedipus Tyrannus," given by the company from the Royal Theatre on a temporary stage erected in the Stadium. King George and all the members of the royal family attended both occasions, and there was an enormous outpouring of the populace to see both spectacles.

abstract: BOSTON, April 28. -- Prices of copper stocks have been depressed this week, in common with others, and at times the market has shown little rallying power. Large holders have been indifferent, feeling assured of their tactical strength of position. The market price of the metal is close to 19 cents, and the prospect is for increased demand from now on.

abstract: CINCINNATI, April 29. -- The forgery of $100,000 worth of improvement bonds of Wood County, Ohio, was brought to light to-day. At the same time the mysterious disappearance of Arthur L. Rich, a prominent broker, became known to the general public. It is believed he is now on the way to Honduras, having eluded pursuit by jumping from the window of a Pullman car at Dayton, Ohio.
